  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential Prison Sentences\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Potentially longer sentences for aggravated cases\n- Consecutive sentences possible for multiple counts\n\n2. Financial Penalties\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n\n3. Asset Forfeiture\n- Government can seize assets connected to laundering activities\n- Can include money, property, and other valuables used in or derived from illegal transactions\n\n4. Additional Consequences\n- Potential criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Difficulties obtaining future employment\n- Immigration consequences for non-citizens\n\n5. Specific Statutes\n- Primarily prosecuted under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957\n- Penalties can vary based on specific circumstances and underlying criminal activity\n\nThe exact penalties depend on factors like transaction amount, intent, criminal history, and specific circumstances of the offense. Consulting a federal criminal defense attorney would provide the most precise guidance for individual situations.",
